tively about it using tools such as metaphor, analogy, and typology. He guides readers through each step of the theorist's art, from observation and naming to concept formation and explanation. To theorize well, you also need a sound knowledge of existing social theory. Swedberg introduces readers to the most important theories and concepts, and discusses how to go about mastering them. If you can think, you can also learn to theorize. This book shows you how.Concise and accessible, The Art of Social Theory features helpful examples throughout, and also provides practical exercises that enable readers to learn through doing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aSociologyxMethodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aArchimedes.  aCharles S. Peirce.  aWilliam Whewell.  aabduction.  aanalogies.  aanalogon.  aanalogy.  aart.  aclassification.  acognitive science.  acolligation.  aconcept.  acreative theorizing.  acreative work.  acreativity.  adiagrams.  adiscovery.  aempirical material.  aexplanation.  aguessing.  aheuristic stance.  aheuristics.  ahypothesis.  aimagination.  ajustification.  aknowledge.  ametaphor.  ametaphors.  anaming.  aobservation.  apattern recognition.  apatterns.  apractical exercises.  apreliminary data.  areasoning.  aresearch process.  aresearcher.  aretroduction.  ascientific analysis.  ascientific research.  asocial data.  asocial life.  asocial science.  asocial scientists.  asocial theory.  atheoretical imagination.  atheorizing.  atheory.  athinking.  atypology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400850358zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps